The paper discusses a general framework for search and detection algorithms in dynamic networks, with applications in monitoring new contents on the web, analyzing influence properties in social networks, and detecting failure propagation on large electronic circuits. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.SD (Software Engineering), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.SOC (Computational Social Science), and cs.IR (Information Retrieval). However, given the focus on social networks and influence properties, cs.SI and cs.SOC are the most likely sub-categories. The use of optimization algorithms and sampling methods also suggests a possible fit with cs.DS and cs.IR.
